         <entryFree xml:id="k000258" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000258-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt" source="#biblk000258-1">tiao</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000258-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">跳</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000258-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">跳</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000258-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin" source="#biblk000258-2">tiào</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000258-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile" source="#biblk000258-3">t'iao</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000258-6" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000258-1">step</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000258-6" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000258-4">jump</term>
            <idno type="URI">https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000258</idno>
            <note type="Note">
               <p xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000258-5">Literally meaning “jump” or "step," in <title>Yingzao Fashi</title> (1103) the term tiao is used to refer to either horizontal bracket arms (gong <term ref="/keyword/k000169">栱</term>) or slanted bracket arms (ang <term ref="/keyword/k000103">昂</term>) projecting perpendicularly from the wall plane. One tiao refers to one outward projection, and there can be up to five projections in a bracket set.</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#biblk000258-5">在《营造法式》(1103) 中是斗栱做法術語，即指挑出<term ref="/keyword/k000169">栱</term>或<term ref="/keyword/k000103">昂</term>。挑出一层，称一跳，最多至五跳。</p>
            </note>
            <note type="related concepts">
               <p><term ref="/keyword/k000193">跳頭 tiàotóu</term></p>
            </note>
